  "prompt": "Why did the government of India introduced a 2000 rupee note instead of a new 1000 rupee note?",
  "response": "The government of India introduced the \u20b92000 note in November 2016 as part of its demonetization initiative, which aimed to combat black money, counterfeit currency, and corruption. The decision to introduce a \u20b92000 note rather than a new \u20b91000 note served multiple purposes:\n\n1. **Higher Denomination**: The \u20b92000 note was a way to quickly provide liquidity to the economy post-demonetization by enabling high-value transactions without the need to print a large volume of lower denomination notes.\n\n2. **Ease of Transition**: By introducing a new high denomination note, the government aimed to minimize the disruption caused by the sudden withdrawal of the \u20b9500 and \u20b91000 notes from circulation.\n\n3. **Reduction in Cash Handling**: A \u20b92000 note allows individuals and businesses to conduct larger transactions with fewer physical notes, which can help streamline cash handling and reduce the risk associated with carrying large sums.\n\n4. **Counterfeit Prevention**: The introduction of the \u20b92000 note included advanced security features to make counterfeiting more difficult compared to older notes, thus addressing one of the primary concerns leading to the demonetization.\n\nThe choice not to reintroduce the \u20b91000 note was likely a strategic decision to prevent the same issues that had plagued the old notes re-emerging, while still facilitating smooth cash transactions in the economy. Ultimately, the \u20b92000 note was intended to modernize the Indian currency system while addressing specific economic challenges at that time.",
